bug.short_desc: Filezilla GUI broken after upgrade to Fedora 24

long_desc.thetext:
Description of problem: Filezilla GUI is broken after upgrade to Fedora 24. When is FileZilla window maximized, "widgets" are taking only original size of window (as if it was unamximized) and cannot be enlarged.
Completely broken when unmaximized.
Version-Release number of selected component (if applicable): filezilla-3.16.1-1 gtk3-3.20.3-0
How reproducible: Always
Steps to Reproduce: 1. Run filezilla
I'm also seeing breakage on my system, but different appearances. I'm using KDE with SDDM. Menus on top bar are squished to the left. Screenshots to follow.

Created attachment 1171078 Filezilla unmaximized
Filezilla window under KDE, unmaximized.

Created attachment 1171079 Filezilla maximized (KDE)
Filezilla window under KDE, maximized.

Could this be a gtk issue? Trying a variety of random programs after updating to F24 it seems that a small group of programs display similar display issues such as menu items all being squished to the left.
Programs tested that display this problem under KDE (small quick random sample) are:
libreoffice gramps filezilla ghex gnome system monitor remote desktop viewer gchem3d
Other gnome programs don't display this problem. Will trying under other display environments to see if issue is KDE specific or more general.

Ok, before trying other DEs I looked to see if there were other settings that might cause this under KDE. I see a new choice under "application style" in application settings: "Gnome application style (GTK)" which I don't see on my F23 system, so let's play with that.
After system update the default settings were: GTK2 theme: Zukitwo GTK3 theme: Zukitwo Font: Cantarell 10 Cursor theme: Adwaita Icon theme: Gnome Fallback theme: <blank>
I played around with the choices and got applications to display properly with: GTK2 theme: Adwaita GTK3 theme: Default Font: Cantarell 10 Cursor theme: Adwaita Icon theme: Breeze Fallback theme: Gnome
Does seem a bit touchy as other themes did not work. Not sure if it's specific combinations that must be used.
What display environment did the original reporter use?
